    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nwhen write a `nvim -l` scripts, to wait for all events I use `vim.wait()` in a loop.\nbut `vim.wait(0)` will use 100% of a cpu core. Can we remove this condition to make `vim.wait(-1)` wait forever?\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e42050f4aed5ee332cc95bacd622bfbc9a31dbe0/src/nvim/lua/executor.c#L455-L457\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/442f297c633375074a88133a9b3d8c08cad58dd0/src/nvim/event/loop.c#L76\n\nso `while true do vim.wait(0) end` can be used as -> `vim.wait(-1)`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`vim.wait(-1)` wait forever.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "or loop set a platform-related large value, which also seems fine? \n\nhttps://github.com/willothy/flatten.nvim/blob/ea99c8c7e9ee4fd66d749a102462d5610126b988/lua/flatten/guest.lua#L15-L18\n\nOr just wonder if this can be make more opaque to user, in most case I have to write this guard in the scripts to avoid nvim quit early",
